{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_yorkie_ver01/data/sn84026749/00280764747/1921010201/0600.xml":{"full_text":"EESBUSINESS\nGAIN IN 1921\nAr*ber Wall Douglas Hopes for\nReturn of Prosperity In\nNext 3 Months.\nThe year 1921 opens with \"poor\nbut sound\" business conditions\nthroughout the United States and\np for better conditions by\nsp according to the semi-an\nn usiness review of Archer Wall\nDouglas, chairman of the Committee\non Statistics and Standards of the\nChambir of Commerce of the United\nStates.\nWANT BETTER TEAMWORK. C\nA determined and constructive ef- t\nfort is being exerted to bring about v\na change for the better by teamwqrk u\nand co-oeration, Douglas stated. En- n\ntire absence of any apprehension of a t,\nimeney panic is the most encouraging a,\nfeature ot the stuation. according to\nDouglas.\nHow long the present situation will\nlast is a subject of much speculation\nand inquiry,\" says Douglas. '\"The\ngeneral thought in that the winter\nmonths will be quiet and that as\nspring opens there will be an ap- l\npreciable change for the better. Y\n\"In the cotton section there are tc\nthose who feel that the first six ni\nmonths of the year will show a con- w\ntinuous, monotony of dull buisness. m\nin the industriaJ dihtricts there is a\ngeneral feeling that the situation c(\nwill improve when prices of commodi- pi\nties reach a figure that will tempt it\nthe ultimate consumer to begin pur- p1\nchasing for other than his immediate fi\nwants. It is rather significant that fI\nsome sales, can be made at bargain Y\nfigures, but very few at moderate w\nconcessions. The answer apparently\nis, therefore, that when the readjust- PI\nment now in active operation has re- M\nsuited in a sufficiently low level of n\nprices for manufactured commodities, Ir\nbusiness in the industrial districts\nwill assume more normal proportions.\nbi\nFARMER IN DISTItESS.\n\"We have the curious paradox in ,I\nthis country at this time of the great- pl\neLt harvest ever gathered, and conse- m\nquently the greatest a.nount of agri\ncultural wealth, in quantity, that we ri\nhave ever known. with the lack of tj\nthe factor of ready translation into o1\nliquid capital; and In the midst of In- a,\ncredible plenty on every hand the fi\ncountryside is still in sore distress a,\nThe farmer is particularly short of fl\nfunds since he has marketed so small w\na portion of his crop, and as the of\ncountry banks are already loaned up\nto their limit, it is difficult in fact. 1i\nalmost impossible-for the merchants m\nand farmers to obtain further credit.\n\"The farmer is most unwilling to\nsell his products at present low fig\nures, and is not doing so. save under\n;tress of necessity or because of\npressure brought by merchants and\nbanks to settle his accounts.\n\"From the viewpoint of the farmer,\nit may be said that he purchased his 5\nhouse and farm equipment last spring r,\nat the peak of high prices and paid tc\nfor the labor the largest wages with- c:\nIn his memory. Now, before ie ha-' b;\nopportunity to dispose of his prod\nucts, the prices decline from 40 to 50\nper cent, until they reach flgures\nvhich seem to him entirely unremu\nne;ative. In addition, as is always a\nthe case in periods of low prices, he n\nfinds that there is practically no mar- it\nket for some of his goods. e\n\"Many merchants are engaged it.\ncollecting bills due rather than in- tf\ncurring new commitments, and con- u\nsequently their buying is confined d\nCREAM\nUh-um-m I\nt Patritic U. TOm\nMsts Svcces\nTo StaiW %igL\nBOGALUSA, La., Jan. 2. -Fulk\na this town today were dusting of\nL big sign placed directly in fron\nif the Union Station warning a]\nEolheviks and red agitators t\n'move on,\" and were congratulal\nng themselves on having the mom\n)atriotic town in the United State,\nrhe big sign In front of the rail\nWay station wAs erected by $h\n,oyalty League of Dogalusa. coln\n)osed of ex-service men. It reads:\n\"In 1925 Bogalusa wants 3.00\ngood citizens.\n\"Advice to Bolsheviks and agita\nors:\n\"Move on. This is no place to\nV ou.\n\"By order of the Helf-Preserva\nlion and Loyalty League.\"\nThe sign has filled its purpoof\nnembers of the league Say. It an\nreds had seen the sign they bav\nieeded and moved on. and there I,\niot one in Bogalusa today.\nfter the example set by the farm4\nLrgely to things of immediate nee\nollections are naturally slow und\niese conditions. Merchants are r\nIsing drastically their credit Oyster\nnder the stress of necessity, and\nany cases thp retailers In the cou\ny districts gre confining themselv\nrictly to cash transactions.\"\nLEVELAND CONFIDENT\nAS NEW YEAR DAN\nCLEVELAND, Ohio. Jan. 2.--Clev\nnd bankers look toward the Ne\nar with confidence that the tret\nward prosperity and normal bui\nmns activities, already under wa\nill become more markeed an t)\nonths pass.\n\"Further reductions in prices\nimmodities and jabor may be e:\n'eted,\" said J. It. Nutt, president\ne Citizens' Savings and Trust Cor\niny, which tomorrow unites wi\nve other banks to form the large\nnancial institution outside of Ne\nDrk or Chicago in the United StatE\nith a capital of $33,000.000 and re\nurces exceeding $330,000,000. \"T\nocess of readjustment, begun son\nonths ago, is still under way, at\ntural laws are working out the\nevitable effect.\n\"Bassic conditions, however, a\nund, and as the year grows old\nisiness should gradually impro,\nhen merchants have cleared the\nelves of high priced godds and r,\naced them with tho e bought at\nore moderate figure.\"\n\"Before another New Year's Day a\nves,\" said F. Hi. (;off. president\nw Cleveland Trust Company. a\nher large institution. \"well ma\n;ed firms should be vhanging ro\ngures to black in their monthly ba\nwe sheets. l'rices and wages a!\nIling now in the same order\nhivh they went up with the outbrei\nthe war six years ago.\n\"There is nothing surprising at\ntIle that is alarming in these mov\nents.\"\nRISCO IS CONFIDENT\nSITUATION IS SOUN\n1AN FRANCISCO. Jan. 2. -,on\nmnee that America is fundamental\nund and that courage and faith w\nstore American business and finan\nnormal stablized condition, w\npressed by leading Sin Francis\ntnkers in statements today.\nHunt Escaped Convicts.\nMONTGOMERY. Ala.. Jan. Poli\nre today scouring the ountry f\nussell Shouse and Charlie Winnal\nng-term prisoners, who made th,\nitape from Aldrich mines.\nShouse was serving a ten-year se\nnee for highway robbery. Winna!,\nas serving a life sentence for m'\nr.\na\nL G. .-S C\ni PAT ..4\nFRANCEFIGHTS\nDISARMAMENT\nSenator Says U. S. Will Suffer\nHuge Loss If Borah\nResolution Passes.\nBy SENATOR JOSEPH I. FRANCE,\nr Wr,ie1 fte Uiversail serviee.\nA resolution by Senator Borah t\nauthorizing the President to take up\nthe question of disarmament with\nr Great Britain and Japan will prob\nably be reported from the Senate\nCommittee on Foreign Affairs to- 11\nmorrow.\nIt provides that proposed in- e\nd. creases in our battleship building\nsr program shall be curtailed 50 per\ns- cent during the ensuing year and\nas 50 per cent for each succeeding year, C\non condition England and Japan\nSwill consent to curtail their building\nl programs in similar manner and\nike deegre.t\nSCHusJ ArRACTIVS.\n\"To peace lovers and friends of dis\narmament the scheme seems attrac\nS tive and feasible. They speak of\nAmerica paving the way for world die\narmament by showing her own will\ne- ingnems to disarm. The fact that G.reaf\nBritain and Japan, the only remaining\nstrong naval powers, are to curtail their\nbuilding programs in concert with ih,\nUnited States makes the plan doubly t\ne attractive.\n\"Nevertheless, I Intend to fight the\nproposed measure to the end. believ- 4\ning it to be fraught with danger to\nour country and a program that Great\nBritain and Japan may well accept\nwith a hidden smile. My reasons for\nt this decision are as follows:\n\"Congrems in 1916 adopted a naval\nbuilding program providing for the\nconstruotion of ten first class battle\nle ships and six battle cruisers, the\n1 period of construction to extend over\n(I three' years. The total 'ost will be\nir not less than $200.000.000.\n\"'rhat program has been partly car\nSried out. Eight or more of the battle\nr ships tnd practicilly all of the battle\ncruisrs are well under way and con- I\nIr tracts involving millions of dollars\nare outstanding for fabricated steel\nto build the remairnig ships.\nGreat Britain hits at pre-sent not\na single capital battlship in coursm\n)f construction. ad is conentrating\nhalmost exclusively ..n Improving I\ninethods of uindersea and air tightig.\nd lpan has adopted an extensie naval\nbuilding program, but has not yet\n.1 proceeded to carry it into) effect. E\nn The effect of this naval holiday\nk p>lan would. therefore, be to force tv,\nto halt our builing program. Fcrat)\nd cur half-eompleted battleships. amei\n(\"atlPfl contiacts for steel aind other\nflitinigs that weuld cost many nil\nlions of dollars, while our naval\nrivals, 4 ;reat Britain andl lapan,\nwould suffer no I ss or inconvenienvee.\nD n effect it would guarantee that\nthe present weainess of fur naval\nstrength as ecmipared to ;rvat Irit\nain would continue. and that we would\nnot attempt to rival her power on\nthe Pea. The resolution says nothing\nabout equalization of naval strength,\nand provides only for outting deown\npresent and future building pro\ngrams.\n\"Doubtless Japan and Great Brit\nsin would eagerly seIze .tuen all p\npIortuitly it it is presented, but we\nwill be showing lee,or statesmanship\nto do suvih a thing. If our present\nr naval program is carried to conclu\nsion we will have within a few\nyears the greatest navy in the\nle world, one that will compel respect\nr- for our flag and our countrymen in\nevery land.\nO\nEAM S p\nn\nC\nShaw Sa All Ireland\nWill Unit p to Prevent\nHome Rule Partition\nC...a.il ..,n.9 Page.\nuch schemes the ancient Incantations in the names of the Pope\ntpd King William are powerless.\nWhen this in turn is realized, the second VOLTE FACE\nvill take place, and in due time be announced by Sir \"Edward\n,arson to the Rupert of the Covenant. Everywhere in Europe\nlow the industrial employers are holding Socialism off in spite\nif the growing urban Labor party by getting their backs a ainst\nhe immense and almost immovable conservative mass of the\n>easant proprietors.\nIn Ireland that mass is composed mainly of Sinn Fein\narmers, who, though perfectly ready to kick the King's crown\nito the Shannon, may be depended on not to budge an inch\nehen -they are threatened by their laborers with high rates, high\nrages and field legislation..\nPirtition will mean, when the situation develops, an\nighteenth century individualist southern Ireland with the farmers'\n>rotits maximized by the co-operation taught them by Sir Horace\n'lunkett, side by side with a Bolshevist Ulster with the dictator\nhi of the proletariat made much less reasonable by democracy\nnd electoral ignorance than the intelligent despotism of trained\nrofessional thinkers and students of political science like Lenin,\nrotsky and Krassin.\nIt is, therefore, for the wage workers of Ulster to demand\nnd support partition, and for the landlords, capitalists, em\nloyers and luxury-tradesmen to call on Sir Edward to declare\nhat they will not suffer their beloved country to be rent in\nwain: that Ireland's watchword must be \"United we stand,\nlivided we fall;\" that all Irishmen are brothers; that Romanism\n.nd Anglicanism are mere superficial variants of the same\n.atholic faith, and that the true unity of unionism is the unity\nf the parliament of Ireland, one and indivisible.\nOne Remedy Only, \"Conscience.\"\nI do not suppose that your readers will believe this until\nt actually happens, any more than they believed my previons\norecast until it was fulfilled, by which time they had forgotten\nhat I made it; still,. I think it worth recording, as there may\ne an intelligent person here and there capable of being con\ninced by it. We are sufficiently embittered and perplexed by\n)ld antagonisms without the added horror of believing them to be\nrreconcilable, when in fact they are bound to dissolve presently\nnder pressure of circumstances.\nMay I add a word as to the complete change in the militarv\nossibilities of Ireland, and of all other relatively small and poo~r\nountries, which the war office and Marshal Foch have evidently\nmnpressed on the prime minister and on Mr. Winston Churchill\niith terrifying effect, Ireland being now described by Mr.\nhurchill with perfect seriousness as \"a fearful danger\" to the\nritish Empire.\nChange Produced By War.\nThis change has been produced by the war, which has\nroved that the most formidable armaments are not those costly\nattleships and big battalions which rich and populous countrie~s\n)nly can afford, but cheap submarines and aeroplanes, cheaper\nombs and floating mines, still cheaper poison gases, and, cheap\nst of all, infected and consequently infectious microbes.\nThese things unquestionably do make small communities\nar more dangerous to large ones than they were ten years ago.\n3ut' they are not a reason for subjugating small communities,\n>ecause it is part of their danger that they elude mere subjuga\nion, and can be removed only by extermination. They also\nnake large communities quite horrilly dangerous -for example,\nrance is enormousiv more danerouis to England than Ireland\ns; and a war of extermination waged between France and Eng\nand in pursuit of the illusion of security would exterminate civi\nization.\nThere is one remedy, and only one, and that remedy is\n:onscience. Recommend it to the consideration of the next\n)erson in Ireland, to whichever side he may belong, who feels\nempted by the devil to commit murder.\n33 Own 2 P. C. of U.S.\nRiches; Hold 6 Billion\nThirty-three individuals nwn average inenme from the property\ner cent of the entire American of these 23.000 millionaires is 