uests will be e childres of work\npr from other landt-fathere wno\ncannot agord to eod their childrin\nabroad for medieal treatment.\nN FAMOVII 1PLACI.\nThe Atstrin workingman, poverty\nstriei s they are, have rented one\nof the meet fameous palaces In the\nworld-the Summer retreat of the\nAuAlan Imperorm, in Schobrun. a\ngreat pagh with garde\"., fountains,\nstretehs of greesaward and shaded\nlanes. This plae. where in the past\nmoo have plotted for war has become\na home a4 Sohool where the children\nof worklagmesn are planning for\nI wont to Sehoubrun with the man\nwho more than anyone else is re\naposible for this idea. I have men\ntioned him before in these little\nsketehes of Austria-Max Winter, the\nVie. Burgomaster of Vienna. He is\na little man with a poi%ted board and\nthe ind of sparkling eyes which\nwould Mao him an ideal sants Claus.\nHe is one of the most beloved men in\nAustria. When he walked up the\nbroad roadway leading to the casti,\nand bordered by tall chestnuts,\ntrimmed li French style into a sort\nof gigantic green hedge wall. the\nchildren spied him from afar, and\ncame catapulting out into the Noven.\nher drissle to meet him. clasping him\naround the legs. climbing up his sides\nand emitting little squeals of delight.\nIf the children of Au.ria could vote\nhe would n'ot be the Vice-Mayor of\nVienna. He would- be president of\nthe Republic. I'm not sure that they\nwouldn't restore the monarchy and\nmake him King.\nIn the rooms where ladies in wait\njug to the Empress used to steep\nthere are rows and rows of little iron\ncots. The former suite of a prince is\na workshop for small boys. In a\ngrand salon we saw a dozen young\ncirlp being put through calisthenic\n'exerclies.\nONLY ONE DATNTUI.\n\"There is only one trouble with this\ncastle.\" said Dr. Winter. ruefully. \"it\nhas only one bathtub. Workingmen's\nchildren seem to like bathtubs better\nthan the Hapsburgs did.\"\nThe Association of the Friends of\nChildren existed in the early dayx of\nthe war. Then it was a charitable\norganizaUon of the well-to-do, for the\nproletariat. In 1916 the workmen of\nAustria took over its management\nthemselves. It was bankrupt then,\nand they built up the present finan\ncial standing by voluntarily taxing\nthemselves per cent on all their\nearnings. In 100 factories in Vienna\nevery workingman pays this tax to\nthe children\n\"The children of the Austrian work\nera have no homes now.\" said Dr.\nWinter. \"The rooms where they live\nare unheated, and are often stripped\nof furniture. But it is wond-rful\nwhat people can do. even in poverty.\nif they stick together and pool their\nresources.\n\"We have opened etations thrnugh\nout the city. where the children are\ncared for all the time out of school\nhours. In there statiois they are\ngiven two -Is every day, are su\npervised in playing, singing and danc\ning in warn and cheerful surround\nIngs, and are taught those things\nwhich are not in hooks or. if they are.\n8eldom reach our children. They\nlearn how to use their hands. how to\nknow birds and animals. trees and\nflowers. and. abov- all, they are\ntaught to appreciat, other nations\nInternationaltsm is instilled into all\nthe teaching.\n\"W aren't able to pay teachers to\nBuy Muslin\nWhen you buy muslin\nof Fruit of the Loom. I\nwell to have a supply orn\ncuts to better advantage1\ning underwear. This\ntime and money.\nFruit of the Loom is I\nfriend of thousands of h\nFor over seventy years:i\nproving itself dependab)\nIt will not turn yellovw\naway in your linen closet\nsmooth finish will be jul\nafter washing.\nMusi\nFor children's garments, wo\nwear, nightgowns, pajamas,\naprons, middy blouses, and pilkc\nof the Loom, 36.-inch width,i ar<\nFruit of the Loom is modi\nstrong, and serviceable.\nBe sure, when you ask to\nLoom, to look for the Fruit\nlabel-picture of fruit in co\nbest stores carry it.\nMade by B.B.& R.KN1\n0? 1111\nee\nLASTINGPEACE\nAUSTRA MSAM\nPeople of Country Educati\nChildren In Evils of W