tions for child care. They ha%\ndone this in the darkest period whiel\nany country has ever gone througi\nwithout asking a cent from those out\nside their ranks, or without a kronei\nof subsidy. It has come out of thr i\nown neager wages.\nThey lot only preach interdepend\nvnce and brothtrly love between na\ntions to their children. but they gi v\nthem a chance to practice it. Thi\ncoming spring the children of Au.+\ntrina will invite the chibfiren of Frat\nItaly. Switzerland. Norway, Vnnglani\nAwho are sufferiyg from rheumatism vr\nother Ills for which the famous Au.,\nr3m\nlook after the\"e 610e,S\" be eos\ntinuod. \"so 80644ity for6ed s\nwork out as Idea which 1as boo\nenailngly successful. WAdidn'twas\nto separate children fre thar pa\nonto too much. anyway. ead we 4\ncId*d that since most parents knowsa\nleast one thing very well. they e90\nteach it not only to their own chil\ndres but to others. Fathers who as\ncarpenters, for instance. can te\nmanual training quite as well as won\nteachers of that subject. Mothers who\nare clever cooks can teach eeoking\nFathers who are taxidermist. or (us\nrers. know more about anmals tas\nmany a professor of natural his\"tes\nWe have hundreds of clever parent\nwhoae talents as teacbers are neve\n\"o these fathers and m3tbe\nserve In turn at the various staties\nOf course, they aren't paid. The:\nwork for the pleasure that they or\ngiving their own children and others.'\nDr. Winter took Ve to one of thee\nstations. It has been a former bar\nracks. Just a big bare, room. box\nwarm and bright. its walls decorateo\nwith pictures and exhibits and aI\nmanner of interesting things. Th\nchildren rushed out to meet us, an\nwe had to shake hands all aroum\nwhile they gave us the association'i\ngreeting, \"Freundschaft.\" \"Friadli.\ntiess.\" Poor little beggars. Ev-sn tho\ninxious care of their organised fa\nthere and mothers couldn't keel\naway from their faces the marks oi\nbad food, and too little of even that\nBut here they were.